diff:1670622315:1670614285:=52,68c52%0a%3c #foxbegin 221209-214515-988770#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Trust & Accents %0a%3c -> - pwchan%0a%3c -> [-09.12.2022 - 13:45-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221209-214515-988770 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/the-brain-doubts-accent/%0a%3c %0a%3c The above article provides a bit of insight as to why workplace discrimination toward those with accents occurs. Mainly, employers may see accents as an impairment of cooperation and work. While it is true that accents, for a native speaker of the "standard" form of the language, are more difficult to understand, this should not change how trustworthy the information itself actually is. However, a study noted in this article found that a foreign or different accent would make the exact same message or statement seem less trustworthy to the participants. This drop in trust could be instrumental to the issue of workplace discrimination as a result of how one speaks. %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221209-214515-988770#%0a---%0a> %0a
